The translation of "自由国际秩序之后" into English is "Following the自由国际秩序" or more naturally "After the liberal international order." Depending on the context, you might also say "Beyond the liberal international order" or "In the wake of the liberal international order."
CAMBRIDGE – Many analysts see the rise of China and US President Donald Trump’s election as marking the end of the liberal international order.
But should he try to revive it if Joe Biden defeats Trump in the November election?
Perhaps the outcome will not be like that, but he must find some alternative option.
Critics are right to point out that the order established by the United States after 1945 was neither genuinely global nor consistently free.
It excludes more than half the world (including the Soviet bloc and China) and includes many authoritarian countries.
The U.S. hegemony is always overstated.
Nevertheless, the strongest countries must lead in creating global public goods, or they will not be provided—and Americans will suffer as a result.
The current pandemic is a good example of this.
A realistic objective for the Biden administration should be to establish a rules-based international system where different countries participate in addressing various issues.
Will China and Russia be willing to participate?
During the 1990s and the 21st century, neither country was able to balance against American power, which remained执着于 pursuing free values at the expense of sovereignty.
The United States bombed Serbia and invaded Iraq without the approval of the United Nations Security Council.
It also supports a Responsibility to Protect (R2P) resolution adopted by the UN General Assembly in 2005, which aims to provide protection for citizens who are subjected to atrocities by their own governments – a principle that the United States invoked in 2011 to justify bombing Libya to protect Benghazi citizens.
Critics describe this record as an act of American hubris in the post-Cold War era, for instance, when Russia and China felt deceived after the NATO-led intervention in Libya ultimately led to regime change – while defenders of the current campaign characterize it as a natural evolution of international humanitarian law.
Regardless, the growth of Chinese and Russian power more strictly limits the scope for liberal interventionism.
What else is left?
Russia and China emphasize the sovereign principles enshrined in the United Nations Charter, which stipulate that states can wage war only in self-defense or with the approval of the Security Council.
Since 1945, the situation of forcefully occupying territory of neighboring countries has been exceedingly rare, and when it does occur, it comes at a hefty price due to sanctions (as with Russia's annexation of Crimea in 2014).
Additionally, the Security Council frequently authorizes the deployment of peacekeeping forces in troubled countries, while political cooperation has also successfully limited the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and ballistic missiles.
This rule-based order dimension remains crucial.
Specifically in terms of economic relations, the world needs to revise the rules.
Even before the pandemic, China’s hybrid state capitalism supported an unfair mercantilist model that distorted the functions of the World Trade Organization.
The result will lead to a decoupling of global supply chains, particularly when national security is threatened.
Despite China complaining about the United States blocking companies like Huawei from building 5G communication networks in the West, the U.S. position aligns with sovereignty claims.
After all, China prevented Google, Facebook, and Twitter from operating within the country for security reasons.
Negotiating new trade rules will help prevent the escalation of decoupling.
At the same time, despite the outbreak of this crisis, cooperation in key financial sectors remains very strong.
On the contrary, the interdependence in the ecological domain creates an insurmountable obstacle in the face of sovereignty, as threats are transboundary in nature.
No matter how much globalization of the economy may stumble, environmental globalization will continue, as it follows biological and physical laws that are not subject to contemporary geo-political logic.
The aforementioned issues threaten everyone, but no country has the capacity to solve them on its own.
In issues like the COVID-19 pandemic and climate change in 2019 and beyond, power also has what is called a positive-sum dimension.
Under such premises, merely contemplating the exercise of power over others is insufficient.
We must also think in terms of exercising power in concert with other countries.
The Paris Climate Agreement and the World Health Organization are beneficial to us and everyone else.
Since Nixon and Mao's meeting in 1972, despite differences in the ideological realm, this has not inhibited cooperation between China and the United States.
The dilemma Biden faces is whether the United States and China can cooperate in producing global public goods while competing against each other in traditional great-power rivalry domains.
The cyber space is a wholly new and important issue - because it has a partially transnational nature but is also subject to sovereign governments.
The internet has been partially fragmented.
Internet freedom of speech and privacy rules can be established within democratic countries, but these rules will not be recognized by authoritarian states.
As the Global Commission on Internet Stability has suggested, if authoritarians also want to achieve connectivity, certain rules that prohibit tampering with the basic structure of the internet would also be in their interest.
But when they use proxies to wage information wars or intervene in elections (which breaches sovereignty), rules need to be strengthened to regulate such actions, akin to the norms negotiated during the Cold War to limit escalations of maritime incidents (even if antagonism in the ideological domain remains).
The United States and like-minded countries must be clear about the norms they intend to uphold and build the necessary deterrence.
Pursuing free values in the cyber space does not mean that the United States unilaterally disarms.
Conversely, the US should distinguish between acceptable forms of soft power such as open persuasion, and harder forms of power like secret information warfare, and it should certainly counteract when another party launches secret information warfare against it.
We can allow Russia and China to air programs and broadcasts openly, but covert coordinated actions on social media and other platforms are not acceptable.
And the U.S. will continue to criticize the human rights records of these countries.
Polls show that the American public wants to avoid military intervention but does not want to exit alliances or multilateral cooperation.
And public values continue to be cherished.
If Biden is elected, the challenge he faces will not be whether to restore the liberal international order.
The question is whether the United States can work with core allies to promote democracy and human rights, while also cooperating with a broader set of countries to manage rule-based international institutions necessary for addressing transnational threats such as climate change, pandemic outbreaks, cyberattacks, terrorism, and economic disruptions.
